'''Gontia''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|ɒ|n|t|i|ə}}) was a [[Celtic polytheism|Celtic]] [[goddess]]. She was the [[tutelary deity]] of the river [[Günz]],<ref>Lauren Adams Gilmour, [https://books.google.com/books?id=QyJmAAAAMAAJ&q= ''Pagans and Christians''], Archaeopress, 2007, p. 24.</ref> near [[Günzburg]] in [[Germany]]. She is known from an inscription on a Roman-era altar at Günzburg ({{lang-la|Guntia}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingeborgschmich.de/Nibelungen/Dokumente/Roemische_Ortsnamensreste.pdf |title=Römische Ortsnamensreste in germanischen Nachfolgernamen |author=Otto Klaus Schmich |date=2004-06-27 |accessdate=2015-03-17}}</ref>) that reads ''Gontiae / sac(rum) / G(aius!) Iulius / Faventianus / |(centurio) leg(ionis) I Ital(icae)'',<ref>''Année Epigraphique'' 1930, 74.</ref> or 'Gaius Julius Faventianus, centurion of the [[Legio I Italica]], (made) this offering to Gontia'. 

She also appears to be connected with the [[Belgium|Belgian]] city [[Ghent]].<ref>Adrian Room, [https://books.google.com/books/about/Placenames_of_the_World.html?id=EdmNngEACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Placenames of the World: Origins and Meanings of the Names for 6,600 Countries, Cities, Territories, Natural Features, and Historic Sites''], McFarland, 2006, p. 144.</ref>

